1. Number.prototype.toString method signature and behavior
- Signature: toString(radix?: number) -> string
- Default radix is 10 (decimal) when parameter omitted
- Returns string representation of number in specified base
- Overrides Object.prototype.toString, does not inherit base behavior
- Method requires Number primitive or Number object as this value
- Throws TypeError if called on non-Number values without coercion

2. Radix parameter handling and constraints
- Radix must be integer in range 2 through 36 inclusive
- Throws RangeError if radix less than 2 or greater than 36
- Radix parameter converted to integer if not already integer
- For bases above 10: letters a-z represent digits 10-35
- Common bases: 2 (binary), 8 (octal), 10 (decimal), 16 (hexadecimal)

3. Binary representation for integers using toString(2)
- (number).toString(2) converts number to binary string representation
- Negative numbers return '-' prefix followed by positive binary representation
- Does NOT return two's complement representation for negative numbers
- JavaScript bitwise operators work on 32-bit signed integers
- Use (n >>> 0).toString(2) for unsigned 32-bit binary representation
- For numbers exceeding 32-bit range, use BigInt for accurate binary conversion

4. Scientific notation and precision handling
- Scientific notation used when radix is 10 and magnitude >= 10^21 or < 10^-6
- Algorithm chooses least significant figures to distinguish from adjacent values
- Floating point precision limitations affect string representation accuracy
- For large integers, multiple equivalent representations exist due to precision
- toString() selects representation with most trailing zeros for given radix

5. Sign preservation and special value handling  
- Negative numbers preserve sign with '-' prefix in all radix bases
- Zero and negative zero both return "0" string
- Infinity returns "Infinity" string regardless of radix
- NaN returns "NaN" string regardless of radix
- Sign handling consistent across all valid radix values

6. BigInt integration for large integer operations
- For integers beyond Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER use BigInt
- BigInt.prototype.toString(radix) works similarly to Number version
- BigInt maintains precision for arbitrarily large integers
- Converting between Number and BigInt may lose precision
- Use BigInt literals (n suffix) or BigInt() constructor for large values

7. Conversion patterns for different number bases
- Binary (base 2): (255).toString(2) returns "11111111"  
- Octal (base 8): (255).toString(8) returns "377"
- Hexadecimal (base 16): (255).toString(16) returns "ff"
- Base conversion chain: parseInt(string, fromBase).toString(toBase)
- Beware precision loss in conversion chains with large numbers

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS
- Performance: Direct toString() faster than string manipulation approaches
- Memory: Large radix conversions may require substantial temporary memory
- Compatibility: toString(radix) supported in all JavaScript environments
- Alternative: toFixed() and toPrecision() for decimal formatting control

REFERENCE DETAILS (API signatures, exact behaviors, patterns)
- Number.prototype.toString(radix?: number) -> string
  - radix: integer 2-36, default 10
  - Throws RangeError if radix out of range
  - Throws TypeError if this is not Number type

- BigInt.prototype.toString(radix?: number) -> string  
  - Same signature and behavior as Number version
  - Works with arbitrarily large integers
  - No precision loss for integer values

- Conversion examples
  - (42).toString() -> "42"
  - (42).toString(2) -> "101010"  
  - (42).toString(16) -> "2a"
  - (-42).toString(2) -> "-101010"
  - (0).toString(2) -> "0"

- Safe integer conversion pattern
  - const safeBinary = (n >>> 0).toString(2)  // unsigned 32-bit
  - const bigBinary = BigInt(n).toString(2)   // arbitrary precision

- Number parsing pattern
  - const decimal = parseInt(binaryStr, 2)
  - const hex = parseInt(binaryStr, 2).toString(16)

